6.18.	However, we reiterated our previous year’s recommendation:
through the Liga ng mga Barangay,  encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;
through the ESMO,  comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only that garbage that are properly segregated;
recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003;  and
initiate the implementation of  Anti-Littering policy ordinances as provided by Section 48 thereof.

We reiterated the recommendations that the Local Chief Executive require the:

Municipal Accountant to  maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards, starting with current year acquisitions until all items are covered; 

GSO to maintain property cards, starting with current year acquisitions until all items are covered; 

Municipal Accountant and the GSO to: 
reconcile the records of the Accounting Office and Property Officer on PPE; and 

submit the RPCPPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records to the Inventory Committee;

Inventory Committee to:
conduct physical count of PPE to determine the existence and condition thereof; and 

follow the new COA Circular 2020-006 re: Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies; 

all concerned Municipal officials to: 
exert effort in the reproduction of titles on all lots owned by the Municipality and 

recognize in the book’s lands owned by the Municipality using the appraised values; and

Municipal Accountant to prepare the Schedule of Depreciation for Depreciable Assets and record depreciation on a monthly basis to ascertain the accuracy of accounting estimates.

We recognized the sincere efforts of the officials in addressing the waste management issues of the Municipality.

However, we reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that:

(a) 	through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;

(b) 	through the ESMO, comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only that garbage that are properly segregated;

(c) ensure that all barangays had existing and operational MRF;

(d) 	recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003;



(e) 	initiate the implementation of its Anti-Littering policy ordinances as provided by Section 48 thereof; and 

(f) 	provide support to the concerned barangay for the construction of secured fence for the MRF for security, health and sanitation purposes.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive require the 

(a) MDRRMC to prepare and submit the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund (LDRRMFIP) indicating the (i) detailed PPAs and the corresponding appropriation classified as either Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) or Capital Outlay (CO); (ii) under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years for ease of monitoring of project implementation;

(b) MDRRMC ensure that the LDRRMF be strictly utilized for the implementation of projects and activities for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation and recovery;

(c) Municipal Accountant to (i) comply with the monthly submission of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF; 

(ii) maintain corresponding Subsidiary Ledger for each type of Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment; and

(iii) ensure that the amount and details of the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF is discussed in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We also recommended that adjusting entry be made for the amount irregularly charged against LDRRMF.

We reiterated our recommendations that the Management:
require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of property, plant and equipment and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) duly reconciled with the accounting and property records;
require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to (i) maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, and (ii) reconcile the respective records of the Accounting Office and Property Office;
direct all concerned Municipal officials to exert effort in the reproduction of titles of all lots owned by the Municipality for recording in the books; and
follow the new COA Circular 2020-006 re: Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances.

We recommended that the

(a) management explain why it failed to comply with the some rules set by LBC 125;

(b)  Municipal Accountant maintain a Special Account in the General Fund for the BGCM;

(c) concerned department to update the uploaded data on the website and make the necessary posting as part of their public disclosure requirements and submit the lacking documents above-stated and henceforth, abide by and observe the existing guidelines on emergency procurements including the preparation and submission of documents for auditing purposes.

We recommended that the Management:

a. comply with the aforementioned rules and regulations in the hiring of JOs and prepare and issue policies and guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring them;

b. immediately strengthen the controls in the hiring of job order by requiring them to submit personal records, undergo interview and document the evaluation of performance to give assurance that the risk identified above are addressed;

c. prepare contract of service instead of job order sheet and incorporate therein the number of man-hours, quantity and duration of the works to be performed by the JOs; and

d. assess and review the necessity of hiring job orders by considering the existence of regular employees who could perform some of the contracted work to maximize the services of the regular employees and minimize the hiring of JOs.

We reiterated the recommendations that the LCE require the:
Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a physical count on the property, plant and equipment to determine the existence and condition of the PPEs; (ii) submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) duly reconciled with the accounting and property records;
Municipal Accountant and the GSO to (i) maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, starting with current year acquisitions until all items are covered; and (ii) reconcile the respective records of the Accounting Office and Property Officer on PPE;
concerned Municipal officials to exert effort in the reproduction of titles on all lots owned by the Municipality and recognize them in the books using appraised values and follow the new COA Circular 2020-006 re: Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies.
1.18.	The Management agreed to the recommendations and assured us that the responsible officials exert their best effort to implement the above guidelines.

