We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the:
Municipal Accountant to (a) prepare and update the Bank Reconciliation Statements of all the depository accounts of the Municipality; (b) draw journal entry for the correction of the over recording and under recording of withdrawals; (c) draw journal entry for the (i) unrecorded, over/under recorded deposits; (ii) unrecorded debit and credit memos; (iii) unrecorded bank interest and bank charges; and (iv) erroneous recordings of Cash in Bank and  Cash in Vault accounts; 

b) 	Municipal Treasurer and the Accountant to (a) record and submit to this Office without delay the disbursement vouchers and supporting papers with transaction value of ₱3,108,247.27and (b) henceforth, invariably comply strictly with pertinent laws, rules and regulations on the recording of financial transactions and rendition of accounts and financial reports within the prescribed period;

c) 	Municipal Treasurer to (a) ensure that  checks drawn tally with the amount of the disbursement voucher; (b) require the concerned payees to refund the overpayment of ₱5,724.00; and (c)  settle the amount of ₱29,200.00 bank charges contained in our Notice of Disallowance and the additional charges of ₱4,800.00 in CY 2014, totaling ₱34,000.00.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive enforce the provision of Section 122 (2) of PD 1445 thru automatic suspension of payment of salaries of officials and employees still in the service who failed to settle said cash advances.  

We also recommended that management require the:

immediate settlement or liquidation of outstanding cash advances in full as of the end of the year except for petty cash advances which should be liquidated within twenty (20) days thereafter;

granting of cash advances only for specific purpose and for expenses which are difficult, impractical or impossible to be paid by check;

monitoring the grant and liquidation of cash advances and refrain from granting additional cash advances unless the previous ones are liquidated/settled; and

acting municipal accountant to reconcile the balances between the GL and Balance per Report on Unliquidated Cash Advance and prepare Subsidiary Ledger to support the GL balance.

We recommended that Management – 

a)  appropriate the 20% Development Fund in accordance with Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2011-1 dated April 13, 2011;

b)  prioritize and implement projects pursuant to the policies and guidelines set forth in the utilization of the 20% Development Fund to improve and attain the socio-economic development of the Municipality and uplift the quality of life of the poorest sector of the community;

c)    carefully plan and review program/projects to be included in the AIP and as much as possible identify cost of each program/projects and avoid lump sum allocation; 

d)  refrain from spending more than the appropriated amount for each program in the AIP; and

e) invest in high-impact capital expenditure projects in the utilization of its 20% Development Fund and refrain from proposing non-capital investment projects under the fund.

We recommended that the: 

Local Chief Executive and the Sanguniang Bayan  prioritize the creation of the mandatory position for the MDRRMO;

Members of the MDRRMC put in place an Incident Command System to properly address emergencies;

MDRRMO refrain from using DRRMF for programs/projects/activities which are not directly related with disaster preparedness, mitigation, response and rescue operations; and

Acting Accountant and the MDRRMO prepare the monthly report on the sources and utilization of the LDRRMF .

